 won and the disease eradicated, the United States demanded that Cuba pledge in its new constitution to maintain the sanitation standards established during the occupation. By situating the history of the fight against yellow fever within its political, military, and economic context, Espinosa reveals that the U.S. program of sanitation and disease control in Cuba was not a charitable endeavor. Instead, she shows that it was an exercise in colonial public health that served to eliminate threats to the continued expansion of U.S. influence in the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMedical policyxHistoryxCuba. 0aMedical policyxHistoryxUnited States. 0aMedical policyzCubaxHistory. 0aMedical policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPublic healthxHistoryxCuba. 0aPublic healthxHistoryxUnited States. 0aPublic healthzCubaxHistory. 0aPublic healthzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aYellow feverxHistoryxCuba. 0aYellow feverxHistoryxSouthern States. 0aYellow feverzCubaxHistory. 0aYellow feverzSouthern StatesxHistory. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226218137423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226218137.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles